data.message: did you know that underneath the foster cta stop there is free parking in that lot so long as you are not facing the building to the east of it?  or, at least it was when i lived on foster and sherman around 5 years ago.  it's worth a closer look!  good luck.

yeah, it's fairly hit or miss there, though, because everyone uses it.  i think that specific area has some weird zoning that prevents the city from setting up parking regulations there.  the apartment complex to its east bought the rights to the spaces facing their building, so i know those are no good anymore.  look for signs, though.  the rules may have changed since this is evanston, after all.  haha.  otherwise, behind 1940 sherman is a huge outdoor paid parking lot.  i'm sure there are signs posted there with contact information.  as well, you can always find non-restricted parking on maple close to evanston's city hall building.  i'm almost positive there are no 2 hour parking limits near that building.

also, if you have a provable evanston address, i highly recommend just buying a city permit.  they are cheap and can be bought at the aforementioned city hall on maple.  if you live on near foster and sherman, you can get a zone a pass for like $70 a year.  sorry for all the information if you already had it.
That's super cheap but I'm pretty sure I'm dorming as of a few hours ago so I don't think that's an option for me

i think there are exceptions for students because all you have to do is prove that you live within a particular residential district.  the housing office can be used to provide such proof if you do not get any bills at your dorm.  the faq has all the relevant information about the process but does not speak about northwestern student parking passes.  it's worth an inquiry.

Capsicum Chinense var. "habanero"

I made habanero chili and I then germinated the seeds from the peppers that I used, on a whim. I got a much higher germination rate than I expected I would have gotten, and therefore I have many more living plants than I can use. These plants are annuals, and they will grow large and produce many habaneros for you in a 5 gallon container, provided that you don't kill the plant with mistreatment. I have grown these before and I will give you any advice you need to grow them successfully. Please understand that I bought those peppers from which I saved seed from a grocery store, and if you've ever grown peppers before, you'll know that they are the most sexually promiscuous plants in a garden. They cross pollenate readily. So I can't guarantee that they are indeed orange habanero plants, but only that they do have orange hab as one parent. If you are interested, contact me at (214) 632 - 7680. Preferably via text message. If you indeed do take one of these plants, I will give you my habanero chili recipe. Alex.
